title: For Sale:  RARE AR15 IN 45ACP BUILT FOR SWAT TEAM IN ALABAMA - ( AR-15 45 ACP )
location: North Carolina, North Carolina, United States
postcontent:
Hello;

More pictures of this gun can be seen here: 

http://imgur.com/a/v7Utc

HISTORY

I bought this AR15 many years ago from a local police officer who stated he was a member of SWAT team in Alabama years before I met him. It was his "secondary gun" as he used his shotgun or handgun as his primary weapon for close quarters combat. He said this gun was strapped across his back for easy access. It does have a nylon sling that goes with it that looks like type of sling a person would use to put the gun out of the way across their back.

He stated that his police department in Alabama contracted a military armorer to assemble these guns in the very late 1980's. He was able to buy this gun for his personal use when he left the department.

This AR15 is compromised of a PWA lower, Olympic Arms upper in 45 ACP, and 3 UZI adapted magazines for an AR15 system. 

LOWER

The PWA "Commando" lower has only a 4 digit serial number and original PREBAN. These low serial number PWA PREBAN lowers have been going for $1,000+ as Gunbroker prices denote. I read somewhere the company that made the lowers for PWA is Lewis Machine & Tool ( LMT ) and are the contact company today. 

UPPER

The 45 ACP Olympic upper is very hard to find as those have not been made in many years. This upper alone goes for over $1,000 with just 1 of these original special plate welded magazines.

MAGAZINES

The 3 special magazines are that of the older UZI brand with the welded plate. These were discontinued many years ago. These very rare HEAVY DUTY magazines were designed for AR15's with 45 ACP uppers. These magazines (if you can even find one) alone were going for $125-$150 EACH a few months ago even before the prices drastically rose. Again, these are very hard to find even ONE...and I have THREE!

FOREARM

You can see the officer mounted a Weaver rail on top of the forend. He told me this was so he could attach a red dot scope to it. And on the left lower side in the front is another Weaver rail. He also told me that was for an attached flashlight.

MISC NOTES

This setup (The Upper, the Lower, and Magazines) would have went well over 
$1,500 a few months ago even before prices rose. You just don't see one of these special AR15's show up very often with these same 1994 original PREBAN components.

I have not shot this, it's been sitting in storage for years. Was getting around to using it, but more pressing bills force me to sell it. 

The trigger feels really nice, but could not tell you what make\model it is, nor do I want to take this apart to find out.

It comes with a very nice case that holds the 3 magazines...and also a sling that does 
not show in the pictures, but can take a picture if needed.

PRICE and TERMS

$1,500 plus shipping.

I live in NC in case you want to do a FTF.

If you live in NC and need it shipped, I can mail it to you WITHOUT an FFL transfer. You just pay shipping and insurance. And I would be willing to drive within a few hours of say Grand Rapids if you say Paypal me the fuel money in advance...so I don't get stuck with the fuel bill and lost time for a no show...fair?

If you live in another state, I will ONLY mail to your FFL and WILL NOT mail to a state 
that does not accept these components...please know your laws and do not waste 
both our times with erroneous information. Again, you pay shipping and insurance.

If any questions...please email me.

Thanks!

postcontent: Sporterized Mauser K98 (Cigarette Rifle). The gunsmith name is unknown. All parts are ORIGINAL to this rifle and bear the Waffenampt acceptance stamp 214. There is absolutely NO rust or pitting on this rifle whatsoever (very rare and unusual for these). The barrel and receiver have a fine patina (no reblue job has ever been done on this). The action locks up tight as a vault. It is a .323 bore with good rifling. Bolt handle has been finely turned to allow for a mounted scope, but doubt you will find rings for it. The stock is in fantastic shape with a couple of minor dings and a small hairline crack on the left side of the forearm. Rifles like these were made by gunsmiths in Germany after the war as bartering tools because their currency wasn't worth anything. Estimated time of work puts it at 1945-1947.  I would like to find this piece of history a good home and an owner who would appreciate it. I am not interested in trades at this time due to trying to offset the cost of a recent purchase. title: Want To Buy:  Outdoor area to shoot
postcontent:
I'm looking for somewhere to go within maybe 30 miles or so from 280/459 merger and enjoy shooting privately on private property without disturbing anyone.  I have been a shooter since my childhood and am very safe and respectful of other's safety and property.  My spouse has taken a strong liking to shooting sports, and I would like to be able to shoot with her occassionally too, and she's much more comfortable outdoors and away from big groups of people.  I have been to a few public outdoor ranges around the state, and while there are many safe people, there are also many people that are dangerous and not courteous or respectful of other shooters.

Up to 100 yards would be great for bench resting rifles, and we would always be respectful and clean up after ourselves whether brass, paper, or any other trash.  If we wanted to shoot any other targets such as clays, we would ok this with you first, and also clean up better than when we found it.  Most targets would be paper or steel.  Most shooting that would be done is .22 handgun/rifle at various distances on paper/steel, handgun up to 20 yards on paper/steel, defensive shotgun on paper/steel up to 30 yards and occasional slug long range, benchrested or tripod rifle up to 100 yards or more if space is available, and skeet shooting (only if allowed due to busted clays everywhere, but would try to clean up as well as possible).  I love to shoot, but I think I get more satisfaction out of watching someone I help such as my spouse grow more confident by putting rounds on target.

If this is something that might interest you, please feel free to contact me.  I did not intend to take away from the other person that recently posted a similar ad, but this is something I have contemplated posting for awhile.  I have lived in Alabama my entire life, but a somewhat recent Bham transplant due to work and living in the city for right now isn't my cup of tea.  I would just like to be able to get outside in nice weather and shoot for a few hours like I used to with not a lot of folks around.  I think it's important also as shooters to pass along good and safe information to new shooters and get as many people interested as possible, such as my new spouse.

Again, if this is something that interests you, perhaps we could work something out such as a range fee or work on the range.  We would like to maybe be able to shoot once a month or so, but with my work schedule this might vary and we can work out details as we go along.  Of course, we would notify you BEFORE every time that we would want to come, and could give you as many days advance notice as you need.  Thanks in advance.

title: For Sale:  Retro Colt 603 clone
postcontent:
Looking to sell my retro build -- a semi-auto clone of a Colt 603 (M16A1). The upper assembly is genuine Colt, CH proof marks, C MP CHROMEBORE 1:12  barrel, MPC on the bolt, faint C on the front sight -- all indicative of a correct/matching 1974-1982 era M16A1 upper. Lower is a NoDak Spud full-fence A1, and receivers are CeraKoted in 'Sniper Grey'. Stock is genuine surplus Colt Type E, with a modern buffer tube and buffer. LPK was treated with naval jelly before installation for color matching, and mag button/trigger guard are anodized in XM Grey, and the selector is a correct "no tick" style. Also has the correct Garand sling.

Everything is in very nice shape. This was not built from one of those junk Israeli M16A1 parts kits that hit the market earlier this year.

Shoots great, nice and accurate too. I have shot about 250rds of Prvi and Wolf 55gr, with no issues.

Will also include three original 20rd Colt mags -- ".223 Cal" marked floorplates indicate pre-1969, and they look like it. 2 of them probably need a new mag spring.

For additional info on the Colt 603 -- http://bpullignwolnet.dotster.com/retroblackrifle/ModGde/RflGde/603A1.html


Asking $1500 FTF in NH, or you pay transfer fee. Shipping to an out of state FFL would be $50. Not interested in any trades -- only looking to sell to fund another project.
